      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I apologize for the earlier confusion; I will strictly adhere to logistics and inventory management principles from now on. The small, recurring variances you are seeing in the Rotterdam electronics section are likely caused by standard operational factors rather than anomalies.\n\nThe most probable cause for these specific discrepancies is **cycle count timing differences**. If the physical counts were taken while new shipments were being put away or if returns were being processed, the system might not have updated the \"Expected Qty\" to match the physical reality yet. For instance, a variance of -8 on SKU-992-A could simply mean 8 units were received and put away after the last system update but before the count was performed.\n\nAnother common factor is **misplaced inventory due to high turnover**. Electronics often have high movement rates, leading to items being temporarily stored in overflow bins, on the wrong shelf, or behind pallets where they are missed during a quick count. This explains why the variance is consistent week-over-week; the same items are consistently being moved or mislabeled.\n\nAdditionally, consider **human error during data entry**. If a warehouse associate manually entered a quantity into the system that was slightly incorrect (e.g., typing 1442 instead of 1",
